commit.message:
Migrate to PySPNEGO (#126)

* Migrate to PySPNEGO

The ntlm_auth library is deprecated in favour of pyspnego. This commit
migrates to this library, patching some methods to ensure dependent code
will continue to work.

* Remove domain parsing tests

PySPNEGO handles the parsing of the domain component of the username

* Add a test for authenticating with an NTLM hash

PySPNEGO allows usage of an NTLM hash in place of a password, so test
that this is functioning properly.

* Update CBT and SessionSecurity code

* Fix up tests

* Update readme

---------

Co-authored-by: Jordan Borean <jborean93@gmail.com>

Merge pull request #97 from t-8ch/master

don't document the unused `session` parameter
don't document the unused `session` parameter

Merge pull request #94 from jborean93/cbt-hashes

Support CBT Hashes larger than SHA256
further improvements around override flags and setting minimum cryptography version
changed process to use cryptography instead
Fixed up tests and get travis to install the latest pip and setuptools before running
Added support for CBT when using hashes that is not MD5/SHA1/SHA256

Merge pull request #89 from nitzmahone/no_parse_upn

Remove domain parsing for UPN-formatted names

Remove domain parsing for UPN-formatted names

Turns out domain should be null for UPN (according to https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/aa378184(v=vs.85).aspx), and breaks default domain handling for alternate UPN suffixes (eg, email-address-as-domain-username). 

Updated tests to match current behavior.

Merge pull request #84 from jborean93/ntlmv2-support

Added support for NTLMv2 Authentication
minor indentation fix
added unicode casting to NTLM messages
changes requested in review, added more checks to server
more changes from pull request review
Removed mocking functions and will just validate the message type instead for the tests. Changed check on whether the socket has a certificate available
Bumped version to 1.0.0

* remove test_server_certificate now that the method has changed and it is harder to mock out
* converted long string to use implicit line continuation to match standards set
* Added more documentation around session_security and what it is used for
* Instead of creating a new socket to get server certificate, it will now reutilise the existing socket

* Changed ntlm dependency to one that support NTLMv2 auth and other NTLM features
* Adding in the ability to let libraries calling requests_ntlm to encrypt and decrypt messages using NTLM signing and sealing
* Added support for Channel Binding Tokens when authenticating
* Updated the tests to match Microsoft documentation
* Updated readme and setup.py to reflect these changes
Remove travis comments.
